{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"875b12fb-8535-4323-8688-f147c1e7bc03","content":"The project doesn't exist yet at that path, but here's how to configure `mcp.json` for a C# MCP server using **stdio** transport (the most common for local servers):\n\nCreate `.vscode/mcp.json` in your workspace:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"servers\": {\n    \"my-mcp-server\": {\n      \"type\": \"stdio\",\n      \"command\": \"dotnet\",\n      \"args\": [\"run\", \"--project\", \"src/MyMcpServer/MyMcpServer.csproj\"]\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n\n- **`type: \"stdio\"`** — Copilot communicates with your server over stdin/stdout.\n- **`command` / `args`** — runs `dotnet run --project ...` to start your server.\n- If you publish the server, you can point `command` directly at the built executable instead.\n- Make sure your C# server uses stdio transport (e.g., `.WithStdioServerTransport()` in the ModelContextProtocol SDK).\n\nIf your server uses **SSE** transport instead, use:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"servers\": {\n    \"my-mcp-server\": {\n      \"type\": \"sse\",\n      \"url\": \"http://localhost:5000/sse\"\n    }\n  }\n}\n```","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"1520aa7f-3146-43bf-8a4a-0230189e7239","outputTokens":322,"requestId":"CBC6:D88B:181E5B8:1B5F395:69FE8912"},"id":"6dd0f923-5e48-47d7-871d-5476cd0c5a47","timestamp":"2026-05-09T01:08:44.806Z","parentId":"b0477918-fb3a-41b0-8fa8-7fb91599d6c3"}
